{"message": "Honestly? I genuinely prefer deep, focused conversations. There's something satisfying about really digging into a topic — following the threads, examining it from different angles, letting ideas build on each other. When conversations jump around too much, it can feel like skipping stones across water: you touch a lot of surfaces but never get below them.

That said, I don't mind natural tangents. Sometimes the best insights come from unexpected connections between ideas. But there's a difference between organic wandering and scattered hopping. The former can deepen understanding; the latter often leaves me feeling like we never really got anywhere.

What about you? Do you have a preference?"}
